Incredibly proud of this campaign I did for @chefjeremyfox + @birdiegsla restaurant, sponsored by @resy + @americanexpress! 8 Nights at Birdie G’s is a Hanukkah-themed dinner series w/ some of Jeremy’s fave chefs from LA and across the country, and the lineup is impressive! I am easily influenced by the food and drink I see scrolling Instagram, so when I saw @smittenkitchen post this cocktail yesterday I knew I had to make it for happy hour! She said it’s her fave and I trust her taste. If you do too, READ ON! I looked through the comments on her original post from a few years ago and saw that people had a lot to say about this drink! Some loved it as is, some used less whiskey, or swapped Aperol for Campari, others used bourbon, equal proportions of everything, and added garnishes. I decided I needed to taste it two ways, for research of course! 🤓 And now I understand why the Boulevardier is popular with both Manhattan and Negroni fans and has been a favorite since the late 1920s.🥃 I included the recipe that I liked best from last night in the drawing, but there are a lot floating around on the internet and in books that use more whiskey, FYI, including Deb’s, which calls for 2oz. Try it a few ways and see what YOU like! 

✍️SWIPE to see this drawing come together and how pretty the drink is in color!

Oooh baby, the artichokes are starting to appear at the markets and I urge you to get some when you see them! I created this illustration to help all the people who pass by them every year, too intimidated to bother. I know they seem like a lot of work, but I think they’re worth it. Also included some tips for choosing a good one (listen for the squeak!), ways to cook them (steaming is easy), and how to eat them if you’ve never had one. Too many times I’ve seen people struggle with the leaves and try to chew them whole. PLEASE don’t do that. Just scrape those petals through your teeth. 🦷 And if you’re wondering what my fave dipping sauce is, well I like to make a Kalamata olive paste, add some lemon juice, then mix that into Vegenaise. If you have extra you can use it on asparagus, roasted potatoes, or fries! Mmmm! 

📖 This is from my book, EAT THIS BOOK! 🤓👍If you liked learning like this, I highly recommend picking up a copy! I tagged a local shop I love but you can get it on Amazon too.

#artichoke #foodknowledge #foodillustration

Have I told you about my Sketchbook Diary? It’s my new daily drawing habit, and I love it! I always thought keeping a daily sketchbook would be hard because what would you think of to draw every single day and how could that be interesting? But I’m constantly inspired by people like @mikelowerystudio @katebingburt @austinkleon and my friend @ed.templeton that draw from life. Incorporating a little diary/journal theme is what sealed the deal for me to want to pick it up. It just feels like I have a little assignment every morning, except I’m the student AND the teacher. As Stacy the student, I try never to just phone it in. As Miss Michelson, I do not accept lazy work and I want to be entertained. These aren’t masterpieces and I don’t spend a lot of time on them, but I kind of love having an illustrated record of things/ life lately. It’s mostly food-focused (what’s new? LOL), drawn in B+W, funny, energetic, cute, and sentimental. I hope these are fun to swipe through and read. Or maybe you’ll just get a cocktail recipe out of it. 😛🤓✍️

#sketchbookdiary #foodillustration 
#dailydrawinghabit

White peaches, yellow peaches, donut peaches, nectarines—I want to eat them all and I bet you do too! This illustration is a cheat sheet so you know how to pick a good one and when’s the best time to eat it. I currently have peaches on the counter that are screaming at me to be eaten, filling up the house with their intoxicating smell. 
🍑Pro Tip: leave them on the counter if they’re hard when you buy them and transfer to the fridge once they’re ripe. They’ll stop ripening a bit that way. 
Also, a cold peach is a great peach for eating over the sink, juices dripping down your hand. Pure summer!☀️

📘Illustration from Eat This Book, by me! If you don’t have it, what are you waiting for?? Buy it ASAP! Yes, Amazon has it, and you can find it on Bookshop and Indiebound too!

Hey, want to see how a little B&W sketchbook drawing transforms into a colored, digital drawing? 👁️👁️

I get a lot of questions about what tools I use, if I work in photoshop, illustrator, on an iPad or tablet, etc, so I thought I’d just show you in a video! 

Almost everything starts in a sketchbook, then I take a photo w/ the iPad or airdrop one in from my phone (so I have it on my iPad). Then I use an Apple Pencil and the Procreate app to trace the drawing and color it in and voila! Pretty simple! If you want to know anything else or something specific, just ask me in the comments! 📝🤓👍

I looove fresh figs, do you? For most of my life I’d only had dried figs, until one day while working at a restaurant, I tried some gorgeous fresh figs they’d prepped for a salad.😛Since then I get excited for August and September when figs start showing up at the market. 

This illustration started like so many of mine do, with nerdy curiosity. I was curious about the different varieties and colors I’d see. I wanted to know how to pick the best, sweetest figs when shopping (heavy figs are the best!), and how I could use them besides standing over the sink and eating 5 at a time. So after a lot of research I made this to try and help anyone else who likes figs but has questions! Feel free to share with IG friends and other fig lovers. It’s a short season, so enjoy! 

#figs #freshfigs #foodknowledge #foodnerd #fooddrawings #foodillustration #foodfacts #eatthisbook

For my 2nd illustration for #negroniweek I HAD to do the Americano! I love this drink. Everyone I make one for loves this drink. I feel bad that I spent so many years not knowing about this drink. You get it😄. Sooooo I highly recommend you try this ESPECIALLY if a Negroni is too strong for you, you like lighter, low-ABV drinks, are a vermouth fan, have a bottle of Campari you need to know how to use, or you just want to try something new! Alsooo, most recipes I see for this don’t include olives (bar snobs don’t come for me!) but they go so nicely in this, so I included it. Use #castelvetrano AKA the best olives. PS if you have an old bottle of vermouth in your cupboard, toss it! Get something new and keep it in the fridge. I learned years ago while working in a restaurant, how most Americans hate vermouth because they’ve only had old, bad vermouth. Think of it like wine (which it’s made from) and how you wouldn’t keep drinking from an open bottle of wine for months and years. Yucky.

IT’S PERSIMMON SEASON so here’s a helpful illustration for an often misunderstood and confusing fruit! Once you read through this you’ll be a persimmon pro, I promise!

Before Eat This Book was a book, I made this specifically to post on IG to try and help people learn about the 2 VERY DIFFERENT varieties. As a persimmon fan, too many people told me they hated this fruit and I was not okay with that. Because I knew, depending on where you grew up you might’ve only seen or tried 1 of these. You might love them or hate them, depending on which one you ate and at what stage of ripeness (see the talk bubble about hard Hachiyas). When I worked at a restaurant, people had such a strong reaction to seeing persimmons on the menu. And it was frustrating seeing recipes call for them but not specifying which variety. So, I just thought—Stace, help the people out! Make a cute drawing explaining it simply and in a casual way so people will actually read it and understand, so I did! ✍️ 
Soooo, if you’re someone who thought you hated persimmons, maybe you’ll give them another try?! 🤷‍♀️ I personally love a hard, cold Fuyu, sliced up with cinnamon sprinkled on top. That’s how my Gramma Mike (as in Michelson) ate them, so I copied her and fell in love. But I have friends who prefer a soft, squishy Hachiya in a bowl with a spoon. Whatever floats your boat! 

🤓If you think this is a cool way to get food smart, you have to grab a copy of my book Eat This Book! I’ve got 98 other foods illustrated and explained like this. It’s pretty fun and good for all ages!📘

IT’S HOSHIGAKI TIME! 😱 This is what was in my mystery video yesterday! Hoshigaki are Japanese-style dried persimmons and they’re such a special little treat! There were lots of questions, so here is an illustration I did about them. I love that they start as firm hachiya persimmons, then totally transform once they’re peeled, hung, and massaged. The massages bring their sugars to the surface. So no, that white powder is not mold, it’s sugar! If you are a persimmon fan and you’ve never had these, I highly recommend tracking some down. 🤓🧡
